note: Une ou plusieurs versions perdues. Selon Bédier, dans le poème perdu, la guerre de Lombardie était motivée, comme historiquement, par le fait qu'Ogier s'était fait le tuteur des fils de Carloman. Metellus de Tegernsee (1150-1160) donne le résumé d'un poème ayant participé à l'établissement de la légende d'Ogier. Le pseudo-Turpin connaissait une trad. où Ogier mourait à Roncevaux. En se fondant sur la KSaga, Aebischer suppose une chanson dans la seconde partie du XIe. Moisan sIII.

note: Très nombreuses allusions anciennes à la légende de Roland, et probable nombreuses versions perdues, de formes diverses. Notamment, il devait y avoir une version antérieure à l'insertion de l'épisode Baligant, et peut-être aussi sans Blancandrin, avec une mort d'Ogier à Roncevaux, peut-être sans Olivier ni Aude. Plus généralement, "On admet l'existence d'une Chanson de Roland différente de celle du manuscrit d'Oxford, aux environs de l'année 1050 (…). Cet archétype est la source du Roland d'Oxford et du Roland de Venise. Nombreuses hypothèses. Moisan sIII. Témoignage aussi de la Nota Emilianense, qui, c. 1065-1075, résumé un Cantar de Rodlane perdu.

claim_freetext: Jean Bodel affirme renouveler une matière préexistante de vieilles chansons. On peut aisément le croire: citations d'une chanson perdue dans la KSaga; épisode de la Gran Conquista de Ultramar, venant d'une version antérieure à J Bodel; 1re et 5e branches de la KS. Existe aussi un Gwidekijn van Sassen néerlandais (même texte?); cf. BESAMUSCA , Bart : Unidentifizierte mittelniederländische Karlsepen. Die «Idée fixe» der mittelniederländischen Literatur als Übersetzungsliteratur, dans Chansons de geste im europäischen Kontext..., pp. 26-35.

note: la trad. anglaise conserve la trace d'une "narration qui se lisait dans un poème (français perdu) en vers de la seconde moitié du XIVe siècle" selon Doutrepont; cf. Moisan sIII. Aussi Valentin und Namelos allemand. Arlima:  L'hypothèse du chercheur suédois G. E. Klemming, supposant qu'il ait existé une chanson de geste intitulée Valentin et Sansnom, est aujourd'hui généralement acceptée par les spécialistes. Cette chanson perdue aurait été composée au XIVe siècle. Elle nous est premièrement connue sous forme d'une adaptation datant de la deuxième moitié du XIVe siècle, et dont il existe des représentants en allemand, en néerlandais et en suédois. La chanson de Valentin et Sansnom nous est aussi conservée sous forme d'un remaniement en prose française (voir ci-dessous).

note: Moisan sIII, Flamand Bauce et Vengeance de Rioul. Épitaphe du flamand Bauce, meurtrier de Guillaume Longue-Épée, dans l'église Saint-Pierre de Gand, témoigne d'une chanson de geste perdue, connue par les résumés de Wace, dans le Roman de Rou, qui évoque une geste qu'il avait entendu dans son enfance (c. 1110-1120), traitant de l'assassinat de Guill. Longue-Épée à Picquigny en 972, et qui ajoutait des traits épiques (Bauce ou Bauches ou Bautes d'Espaigne serait le neveu de Rioul, à qui Guillaume aurait fait crever les yeux, et qui vengerait ainsi son oncle); et Guillaume de Malmesbury, qui en donne un résumé dans le De rebus gestis regum Anglorum, c. 1119-1135. Quelques détails dans Breve chronicon Tornacense et Breve chronicon Turonense.

note: Moisan sIII: à partir d'éléments de Gui de Nanteuil, de la mention d'un "Gaiferus, rex Burdegalensis" dans le PsT, de l'histoire de Lampagnie, fille d'Eudon introduite dans l'Historia episcoporum Autissiodorensium… Voir A. Longnon, Revue des questions historiques, 25 1879 193. Moisan sII rapporte aussi le fait que Saint-Martial de Limoges aurait conservé, au XIe, une bannière prise par Pépin à Waiferius (Adhemar de Chabannes).

Situation assez compliquée, avec un certain nombre d'étapes perdues supposées: selon R. Louis, Girart comte de Vienne…, II 285-287, une chanson primitive du Roussillon fin Xe, transposée au XImed en Bourgogne en 'chanson de Vaubeton', puis, fin XIe, dotée d'une suite qui serait une source du Charles Martel en prose de 1448. Mais, P. Meyer ne pense pas que la source du Charles Martel très différente de la chanson conservée. Hackett, dans son éd., pose l'hypothèse d'un renouvellement pour le GRouss conservé. F. Lot, "Études sur les légendes épiques françaises, II. Girart de Roussillon, Romania, s'interroge sur une hypoth. version utilisée par la KSaga; il critique la position de P. Louis dans R 70 1949, 192-233 et 355-396. Sigebert de Gembloux a été influencé par un texte traitant de cette matière, en vernaculaire ou latin, c. 1083-1105. Résumé dans la Vita Gerardi comitis, § 33-72 ? cf. Moisan sIII.

note: Bossuat: Longnon suppose une rédaction primitive fin Xe, par Bertolai de Laon, un remaniement fin XIe sous l'influence de la maison de Ribemont, et le poème conservé du XII 2/2. J. Flach relève des archaïsmes juridiques incompatibles avec féodalité du XIIe. [crois me souvenir de discussion avec M. Banniard sur ce sujet. Voir sa bibliogr. Dans même volume que G. Hasenohr sur abrév., Peuples d'Europe?]. Autres indices familles de Rumigny, Florennes et Ribemont, selon F. Lot. Cf. aussi Moisan sIII. Allusion de Guilhem de Berguedan aux 4 fils de Herbert dans un sirventes de 1190 prouve que thème connu en Catalogne et que des rédactions plus anciennes existaient. Citations de Claude Fauchet de 259 v., cf. Moisan sIV Fau.

preferred_name: Continuation P de Huon de Bordeaux (Huon roi de feerie…)
note: HuoncpK Cycle de Huon de Bordeaux, continuation ‘Huon, roi de feerie’, en vers décasyllabiques, contenant trois épisodes, Huon, roi de féerie (444 v.), Combat de Huon contre les géants (404 v.) et Huon le desvey (plus de 160 v.). À clarifier. Voir Schafer, Über die Pariser hss. 1451 und 22555…D'après Arlima " Continuation de la chanson de geste Huon de Bordeaux qui se divise en trois épisodes: « Huon, roi des fées », « Le combat contre les géants » et « Huon le desvey ». La fin du dernier épisode est mutilée." Cf. aussi Arlima. On retrouve en partie les mêmes épisodes que dans la continuation du ms. de Turin, mais pas tous ni dans le même ordre. En fait, dans ce cas comme pour les continuations du ms. de Turin, le fait de découper ou non en différents épisodes est assez largement dû aux éditeurs, et pas à la trad. manuscrite. On pourrait découper la continuation P, de la même manière qu'unir les suites du ms. de Turin

note: aussi version franco-italienne. Moisan sIII: possible de supposer une légende assez ancienne; texte conservé serait un remaniement de la fin XIIe. Jean d'Outremeuse, Mireur, donne un résumé avec des particularités que nous n'avons pas dans les versions conservées. Version franco-italienne: conservée ou supposée à partir du Rinaldo da Montalbano? Vers. néerlandaise et allemande, et les mises en prose dans ces langues, auraient eu accès à une version plus ancienne que celles que nous conservons. Citations de Claude Fauchet de 200 v., cf. Moisan sIV Fau. Vers. néerl: S PIJKER , Irene : « Renout van Montalbaen », dans Olifant, 23 (1), 2004, pp. 28-43.

[sur une explication 'hagiographique' des origines, M.A. Peï, Frénch Precursors of the Chanson de Roland, NY, 1948.] Sur le 'cantar de gesta', cf. Bossuat II no 6137 n. Distinguer les versions? Possible Passio Beati Rotolandi latine perdue, dont on garderait quelques traces versifiées, qui aurait servi pour le Roland français, cf. Moisan sIII. Citations de Claude Fauchet, cf. Moisan sIV Fau. Trad. anglaise: H ARDMAN , Philippa : Speaking of Roland. The Middle English «Roland» Fragment in BL MS Lansdowne 388, dans Reading Medieval Studies, 34, 2008, pp. 99-121.

note: Bossuat n°472: "la chanson primitive connue par Hariulf aurait été combinée avec une légende anglaise par un remanieur anglo-normand". Moisan sIII : connue dans le Ponthieu dès 1088. Philippe Mouskés résume une version qui avait court de son temps et diffère déjà du fragm. conservé (c. 1230). Vers 1330, nouvelle rédaction pas conservée, et dérimée en 1415 pour être insérée dans le roman de Loher und Maller. Ressemble à la version Mouskés, mais pas tout à fait.  B ENNETT , Philip E. : A New Look at the «Gormont et Isembart» Fragment, Brussels, Bibliothèque Royale Albert 1 er , MSII, 181, dans Epic Studies..., pp. 123-132

note:
Stemma in Kerr_1994_AnseisCarthage Bossuat sIII no 1031: fragms Anseïs de Carth. et G. de Bourg. Mise en prose notamment dans   Charlemagne et Anseïs (= La cronique associee de Charlemaine et Anseïs ?). Stemmata dans: Johann Alton, Anseis von Karthago, Tübingen, gedruckt für den litterarischen verein in Stuttgart (Bibliothek des
litterarischen vereins in Stuttgart, n°194), 1892; ainsi que Alexander Ferguson Kerr, A critical edition of Anseïs de Cartage, Thèse de l’Université de Reading, sous la direction de Wolfgang van Emden, 1994.
Présence à vérifier dans: Mori, Roberta, Anseïs de Carthage (canzone di gesta del 13. secolo): edizione critica con saggio introduttivo, note al testo e glossario, thèse de doctorat, Università di Bologna, 1998. Ceresato, Floriana, L'Anseïs de Carthage nel Ms. Paris, BnF, Français 1598. Uno studio critico, thèse de doctorat, Università degli studi Roma Tre, 2017.

note:
Existe aussi une version en alexandrins du XIVe, GR3, poème bourguignon, c. 1330-1336, NO de Dijon. Mention de Claude Fauchet, cf. Moisan sIV Fau. Existe un Gerart von Rossiliun.
Le texte original pourrait être bourguignon, ou bien, selon la notice Jonas, «L'auteur du "Girart" original venait probablement de la région de Vienne; sa langue est influencée par le français et le provençal (voir notamment Pfister, 1970c, p. 325). Cette oeuvre ne nous est pas parvenue; le ms. O transmet la copie italienne du remaniement poitevin de ce "Ur-Girart" perdu (voir Pfister, 1970). ». Stemma dans Schweppe 1878.

note: Citation d'un vers par  Claude Fauchet, cf. Moisan sIV Fau. Inclus dans Aspremont (Moisan). Procédérait d'un Girart de Vienne primitif perdu lui aussi (cf Moisan sIII), et R. Louis, "Girart, comte de Vienne…, I 115-176, II 75, 272, 283-284. Connu par l'auteur de l'Entrée d'Espagne (A. Thomas, Nouvelles recherches sur l'Entrée d'Espagne…, 1882, p. 40). Gröber, Grundriss…, 1902, II, 1, p. 808, pense que n'a jamais existé. Voir le CR,  Faral Edmond. Girart de Roussillon. In: Journal des savants, Janvier-juin 1948. pp. 5-15. www.persee.fr/doc/jds_0021-8103_1948_num_1_1_2536 Et  Lot Ferdinand. Encore la légende de Girart de Roussillon, à propos d'un livre récent (deuxième article). In: Romania, tome 70 n°279, 1948. pp. 355-396. DOI : https://doi.org/10.3406/roma.1948.3671 De nombreux remaniements en sont supposés par R. Louis (cf. art. F. Lot).

nature_of_derivations:
Les trois parties de Lohier et Malart se basent probablement sur des chansons antérieures séparées (et perdues auj.): - une reprise de motifs qui figurent dans Floovant; - une chanson perdue sur le conflit des fils de Charlemagne; - un remaniement de Gormont et Isembart.
cf. U. Mölk et D. Kullmann, « Lohier et Malart. Fragment d'une chanson de geste disparue », Romania 110, 1989, p.466-492
note: version néerlandaise. Traduit en prose allemande par Elisabeth de Lorraine-Vaudémont ép. Nassau-Sarrebruck, en 1437, à partir d'une copie du texte français exécuté sur la commande de sa mère, Marguerite de Vaudémont et Joinville, épouse de Ferri, duc de Lorraine, en 1405. Cette même Élisabeth aurait traduit trois autres gestes: Herpin, Sibille, Huge Scheppel. Le ms. de 1405 devait contenir un cycle Lion de Bourges, Reine Sebile, Lohier et Malart, Hugues Capet. Lohier = Lothaire, fils de Charlemagne  Références à Lohier et Malart dans Hugues Capet, Tristan de Nanteuil, Galien li restorés, Godefroid de Bouillon, Charles le Chauve, Ciperis de Vignevaux… On peut supposer au moins 6 mss perdus de cette chanson (cf. Mölk). Fragm. Hessisches Hauptstaatsarchiv Wiesbaden, Abt. 1105, Nr. 40, du XV 1/2. Peut-être du manuscrit même de 1405 déjà cité, en tout cas proche géogr. et chronol. Lien possible aussi avec Arnaïs d'Orléans, Sansonnet, … Car la chronique française dit que "Sansonnet tint depuis le royaume de Hongrie de par Lohier, ung des fils Karlemaine, qui se fist empereur". Sur cette chanson, voir aussi: B USCHINGER , Danielle : Le roman en prose en Allemagne à la fin du Moyen Âge, ses relations avec la France, dans Kultureller Austausch und Literaturgeschichte..., pp. 155-174. Possible survivance de quelques centaines de vers, cf. https://www.arlima.net/il/lohier_et_malart.html , Wiesbaden, Hessisches Hauptstaatsarchiv, Abt 1105 Nr 40 et Mölk, Ulrich, « Lohier et Malart, Fragment eines verschollenden französischen Heldenepos », Nachrichten der Akademie der Wissenschaften Göttingen, t. 1, Philologisch-historische Klasse, Heft 5, 1988, p. 135-164.

note: Louis Gemenne, « Sansonnet : avis de recherche d'un orphelin épique », L'épopée romane 1, t.~2, p.~665-676. Résumé de cette chanson subsiste dans la Chronique Française (Moisan, ChF textes annexes), transcrit par Gaston Paris, Hist poet 403. Utilisée par les auteurs du Couronnement Louis, de la Chronique Saintongeaise, par Aubri de Trois Fontaines, et parmi les sources du Loher und Maller allemand. Cf. Moisan sIII. Existait encore fin XVe, car, dans un Inventaire des bijoux, vêtements, manuscrits et objets précieux appartenant à la comtesse de Montpensier (1443-1474) éd. M. de Boislile, un "Le libre Arnaïs d'Orléans" cf. R 10 447, Bull. Soc. Hist. fr. 17 1880 269-309. (rapporté aussi dans M. J. Devaux, Essai sur les premiers seigneurs de Pithiviers (suite et fin), , Annales Soc. hist. et archéol. du Gâtinais, 4, 1886).

Sur cette chanson, voir Bédier, Joseph, « La légende des "enfances" de Charlemagne et l'histoire de Charles Martel », Studies in Honor of A. Marshall Elliott, in Two Volumes, Baltimore, Johns Hopkins Press; Paris, Champion; Leipzig, Harrassowitz, 1911, t. 1, p. 81-107. Cf. aussi Moisan sIII, avec d'autres réfs. La version néerlandaise pourrait être l'original ! (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elegast )

length_freetext:
'Ik heb lang getwijfeld om in mijn berekening de opsplitsing tussen Ogier I en Ogier II ook te maken
maar ik heb uiteindelijk, net als Van der Have, beslist om dit niet te doen. In mijn berekening schat ik
Ogier van Denemarken op ten minste 23.700 verzen.' Verbraeken 2023, p. 44.

claim_freetext: Bédier assume a single archetypal text for all Tristan version. In addition, Gertrude Schoepperle (Tristan and Isolt : a study of the sources of the romance, Frankfurt, 1913) postulates an Old French model older than the archetype, the Estoire, that she calls B, and is somewhat equivalent to Wendelin Foerster's Ur-Urtristan. Contrarily to Bédier, she does not take the existence of a limited duration of the love potion in Béroul and Eilhart as an argument for a common lost model, but makes it a feature of the original, modified by Thomas.

claim_freetext: This lost work, possibly attributed to Luce del Gat, survives as the first part of all extant versions of the Prose Tristan. It supposedly was a version of the story of Tristan before the contamination by the Arthurian Grail cycle. An incunabulum of it belonged to Marguerite d'Autriche (Debae 1995), according to Jonas

date_of_creation_source: "Composed in Iceland, presumably in the fourteenth century." (K&M) ; "14. oder spätestens frühen 15. Jh." (S&P)
review_note: The crux of the tale is the prophecy that the offspring born to the king and queen of Syria will rule the kingdom after the king's death. An evil duke tries to secure the royal throne for his own progeny and turn the prophecy of royal succession to his own advantage. The king is abducted and secreted in the bed of the duke's daughter, while the duke sleeps with the queen. As prophesied, offspring are born to both king and queen. When the king reveals that he knows about the deception practiced on him, he is attacked by the duke and killed. The queen's son, Constancius, ascends the throne. The greater part of the romance relates the attempts of Adonias, the king's son, to gain the throne of Syria. The romance is characterized by extensive battle accounts.

date_of_creation_source: "Composed in Iceland, presumably in the early fourteenth century." (K&M)
review_note:
The saga relates the fortunes of Jon, a young farmer, who has the gift not only of interpreting dreams, but of divining the dreams of others
 before they are told. Earl Heinrekr of Saxland, who also interprets dreams, envies Jon's superior ability. By eating Jon's heart, the earl
 hopes to acquire Jon's gift, so he commands his wife lngibj9rg to
 murder Jon in his sleep, cut out his heart, and prepare it as food for a meal. Ingibj9rg spares Jon, however, and substitutes the heart of a
 dog. A waxen image of Jon is buried in his stead. The earl's treachery
 comes to light when his brother-in-law, the emperor of Saxland,
 arrives seeking interpretation of an unusual dream. He learns the
 truth about Jon from Ingibj9rg. Subsequently, the earl is banished,
 while Jon receives the earldom and weds Ingibj9rg.

review_note: Derives from an incomplete version of the French Elie de St. Gille, translated by a certain Abbot Robert at the request of Hakon Hakonarson of Norway (1217-63). Like the Strengleikar, Elis saga is preserved in the Norwegian codex De la Gardie 4- 7. Icelandic manuscripts contain a continuation that deviates from the conclusion in the French version.

review_note: Derives from Chretien de Troyes's Arthurian romance Erec et Enide, presumably translated during the thirteenth century in Norway. The work is marked by major structural deviations from the French source: condensation on the one hand, but two major interpolations on the other hand, and a striking dissimilarity to the style of the other translated romances. Erex saga, as we know it from extant manuscripts, suggests the work of one or more Icelandic redactors.

review_note: The saga tells of the three sons of King Flores of Traktia and Princess Elina of Kartagia. Flores had abducted the princess who later bore him three children. During Flores' absence Elina and her children are fetched by her father, but their ship disappears. They are assumed dead, and Flores remarries. When Flores rejects Duke Sintram as suitor for a daughter born of his second marriage, the duke declares war against Flores. In his army are the sons of King Flores. They are captured by their father and during the night before their planned execution they tell each other their life stories. The king overhears them, and realizes they are his sons. A reconciliation ensues.

review_note: The saga, presumably early thirteenth century, extant in two redactions, is related to French, Dutch, and Italian poems, but the immediate source is unknown. Flovent, nephew of Emperor Constantine, incurs his uncle's anger when he kills one of the courtiers on Christmas day. The emperor swears to have Flovent killed should he be captured. Flovent flees northward toward Frakkland with two companions. In the course of his exile Flovent is victorious in one military encounter after another with heathen adversaries. He eventually becomes king of Frakkland and marries the daughter of a heathen king, after she and all of Frakkland have been converted. When heathen armies from Spania besiege Romaborg, Flovent comes to the aid of the emperor. Uncle and nephew are reconciled.

review_note:
The saga relates the amorous liaisons of Gibbon, son of King Vi!hjalmr of Frakkland. He is first brought under the spell of Greka, daughter of King Filip us of Grikkland; she is a type of fairy mistress who remains invisible to him for a long time. After she has finally allowed him to see her, Gibbon is transported back to Paris. Reports of the beauty of the maiden king Florentia, daughter of King Agrippa of Indialand, spur Gibbon to sue for her love. For her sake he overcomes Eskopart, a rival, in battle. A child named Eskopart is the result of the union of
 Gibbon and Florentia. Once more Gibbon is mysteriously transported to Grikkland to enjoy Greka's love. When Eskopart reaches maturity and learns of his father's desertion, he vows vengeance. Father and son are reconciled, however, and Eskopart inherits Frakkland.

review_note: Ector, a descendant of King Priam of Troy, and six knights in his service decide to separate for a year to seek adventure. The fates of the several knights are related serially. All but one of the knights are successful in their undertakings. The sixth knight, Aprival, boasts to King Troilus of Mesopotanea of the superiority of Ector and his companions, but is defeated in a tournament by Eneas, son of King Troilus. When Aprival does not return on the appointed day, Ector leads his army in search of him. Eneas is captured by Ector, but wins his freedom through the intercession of his sister Trobil, who agrees to marry Ector.

review_note: The fosterbrothers Hermann (son of the king of Frakkland) and Jarlmann (son of an earl) are of an age and have been educated together. Hermann sends Jarlmann to Miklagarclr to sue for the hand of Rikilat. She has previously rejected many suitors, butJarlmann wins her for Hermann by means of a magic ring. She cannot return with Jarlmann, however, until the armed forces of another suitor have been repelled. When the wedding finally takes place, Rikilat is mysteriously abducted and imprisoned by the old king Rudent of Serkland who plans to marry her. Jarlmann feigns love for l>orbjc;irg, a giantess who guards Rikilat, and a double wedding ceremony (Rudent-Rikilat, Jarlmann-l>orbj9rg) ensues. Hermann kills the old king and regains his abducted bride, while Jarlmann kills the giantess in the bridal bed. The fosterbrothers and Rikilat return to Frakkland for a second double wedding ceremony. Jarlmann marries the king's sister Herborg and receives half of the kingdom.

review_note: The saga blends motifs from the riddarasogur, thefornaldarsogur, and folk tales. As a baby, Ali flekkr, the son of King Rikarclr of England, is left exposed in the woods but is rescued by peasants. After he marries Porbjorg, a maiden king, a number of misfortunes befall him because he has rejected the love of a female troll. He is temporarily turned into a wolf; in a dream he is wounded and can be cured only by the rejected troll's brothers. Eventually Ali succeeds his father as king of England.

review_note: Only fragments of the original romance are extant, but the plot is preserved for us in rimur that derive from the saga, and in turn generated prose redactions. Hringr, son of King Dagr of Grikkland, is betrothed to Brynhildr, daughter of the king of Gar3ariki. During a prolonged absence by Hringr, Brynhildr is married to Tryggvi, King of Saxland, however, in return for his assistance in defeating another suitor. When Hringr learns of these events he immediately goes to Saxland, where he engages Tryggvi in combat. The rivals become reconciled, and Hringr marries Brynveig, Tryggvi's sister. When a disloyal follower kills Tryggvi, Brynveig dies of grief, and Hringr avenges Tryggvi. The tale ends with the wedding of Hringr and Brynhildr.

review_note: Extant in an older and a younger redaction. A thirteenth-century compilation of translations of several chansons de geste, such as Chanson d'Otinel, Le pelerinage de Charlemagne, Chanson de Roland, Chanson d'Aspremont, as well as Latin historiographical material in the Pseudo-Turpin Chronicle. The work is divided into parts: Karlamagnus saga ok kappa hans; af Fru Olif ok Landres; af Oddgeiri Danska; af Agulando Konungi; af Guitalin Saxa; af Otuel; af Jorsalafer3; af Runzivals Bardaga; af Vilhjalmi Korneis; um kraptaverk ok jartegnir.; Older Norwegian redaction fragmentary, younger Icelandic redaction from the 14th cent - see S&P

review_note: Composed in Iceland, presumably in the fourteenth century. The saga relates in a leisurely, highly rhetorical manner the fortunes of Laicus, King of Athena, and his son Kirialax. Laicus woos and, through combat, wins the hand of Mathidia, daughter of King Dagnus of Syria. After having reached maturity, their son Kirialax sets out to explore the world of his day. The account of his adventures is an extended travelogue-based on learned sources-that includes a visit to Troja and a pilgrimage to Akrsborg to see the True Cross. At the conclusion of his travels, Kirialax marries Florencia, daughter of King Lotharius of Grikkland. He is crowned king of Grikkland and the seven kingdoms subordinate to it. Two sons, Vallterus and Villifer, are born to the royal couple; they emulate father and grandfather.

Perus of Arabia, Klarus's teacher, tries in vain to dissuade him. After repeated frustrations and humiliations Klarus succeeds in marrying Serena. Klarus takes vengeance on his wife for her former cruelty to him, but she proves to be a model

review_note: With his foster-brother R63bert (the son of an earl), Konra3r (son of the emperor of Saxland) who is outstanding in every respect except that ~ he has not learned foreign languages, journeys to Miklagar3r to woo Mathilda, daughter of the king of Grikkland. R63bert, who is skilled in foreign languages, is to speak for Konra3r, but impersonates him and sues for Mathilda's hand. Konra3r learns of the betrayal and with the advice of Mathilda-who has vowed to marry only the son of the emperor ofSaxland-he embarks upon a series of dangerous exploits designed to convince the king of Grikkland of his identity. Finally, he succeeds in obtaining Mathilda as his bride.

The saga is preserved in two redactions, one from around 1300, a longer version from around 1350. " ; "eine der ältesten orginalen Riddarasagas und geht im wesentl. auf das franz. chanson de geste Renaud .... wenn sie auch keine Übersetzung ist; ... zwei Redaktionwn A-kurz 1300; B längeren, ca. 1350" (S&P)
review_note: The nucleus of both versions derives from the French chanson de geste. Earl Amundi has four sons-Vigvarclr, Rognvalldr, Markvarclr, Aclalvarclr-and a daughter. Rognvalldr incurs the anger of the emperor by defeating him in a chess game. The emperor strikes Rognvalldr, and Vigvarclr avenges the insult by killing the emperor. The saga revolves around the clash between the emperor's son Karl and the four brothers, abetted by their brother-in-law Magus who is capable of assuming various disguises. In the end Magus effects a reconciliation between the feuding parties.

review_note: It is unusual among Icelandic riddarasogur in that the conversion to Christianity plays a significant role and indirectly precipitates the conflict. Mirmann kills his heathen father, Earl Hermann of Saxland. Mirmann's mother avenges her husband by giving Mirmann a philtre that makes him a leper. Mirmann journeys to Sicily to be healed by Cecilia, daughter of the king. He is cured and marries her. Subsequently Mirmann journeys to Frakkland to visit his foster-father, King Hlo5ver, whose queen makes Mirmann forget Cecilia and, after the death of Hlo5ver, to marry her. Cecilia disguises herself as Earl Hiringr, joins Mirmann's enemies, vanquishes her husband in combat-at-arms, and leads him away captive. After their reconciliation, Mirmann becomes king of Sicily.

 chastity test-by means of a magic mantle-to which all ladies at Arthur's court must submit as a result of a rash promise by the king.

review_note: The saga relates the repeated failures of suitors to win the beautiful Queen Nitida of Frakkland as wife. Through sorcery Ingi, son of King Hugon of Miklagar5r, succeeds in abducting Nitida, but on their supposed wedding day she disappears by means of a magic stone. Hei5arlogi and Velogi, sons of King Soldan of Serkland, also journey to Paris to sue for her hand, but they and their armies are destroyed. Livorius, son of King Blebarnius of India, manages to abduct Nitida, but on the supposed wedding day Nitida again disappears by magic, taking Syjalin, Livorius' sister along. Under the guise of Eskilvar5r, Livorius once more journeys to Paris, and spends the winter with Nitida. In the spring Nitida shows Livorius/ Eskilvar5r a magic stone by means of which she is able to monitor events all over the world, and reveals that she has known his identity all along. Livorius marries Nitida and Syjalin marries Ingi, one of Nitida's former suitors.

review_note: Presumably either a thirteenth-century translation from a lost version of the French Partenopeus de Blois, or an Icelandic reworking of a lost Norwegian translation. Partalopi, son of King Hloi'>vir of Frakkland, is transported to Miklagari'> where he becomes the lover of Marmoria, a maiden king, who remains invisible to Partalopi, while he remains invisible to her courtiers. Marmoria warns Partalopi that any attempt to see her will result in his death. Partalopi disobeys, but is saved by Marmoria's sister. After a succession of adventures, the lovers become reconciled, marry, and rule jointly.

review_note: Remundr falls in love with a maiden whom he has seen only in his dreams.· Carrying a statue of the maiden he sets off in search of her. Remundr kills Eskupart who claimed to be the maiden's lover, but is himself wounded. Before he died Eskupart prophesied that Remundr could be healed only by the most beautiful woman in the world. After many adventures, Remundr is healed in India by Elina, the woman of his dreams. The saga is indebted to other riddarasogur, especially the Norwegian Tristrams saga.

Nikanor ultimately marries Luneta, daughter of King Benjamin of Akaia in Grikkland. There are many classical and Biblical elements and allusions.

review_note:
The saga relates the exploits of Samson, son of King Arthur of England and Queen Filipia of Hungary, during his search for his beloved Valentina, daughter of King Garlant of Ireland and a maid-in-waiting
 at Arthur's court. Samson is first thwarted and then aided by K vintelin, a shape-shifting thief. The latter steals for him the chastitytesting mantle-the subject of Mottuls saga-from Siguror, son of King Goomundr of Glresisvellir, and this magic garment becomes Samson's gift to his bride Valentina when he finally weds her.

review_note: Ingiger3r, queen of Taricia, and her two sisters, Hildr and Signy, are suffering from a spell placed on them by Hleger3r, their father's concubine. No suitor can please lngiger3r, while Hildr and Signy are turned into animals, When Sigrgar3r, a king's son, woos lngiger3r, she repeatedly makes a fool of him. He leaves Taricia only to return disguised as a merchant. Ingiger3r outwits him when he attempts to abduct her by means of a flying carpet. Finally Sigrgar3r, posing as the viking Knutr, visits lngiger3r with two foster-brothers. The three succeed in breaking the spells. The saga concludes with a triple wedding.

review_note: Sigrgarc, son of King Valdimar of England, obtains a magic harp from the dwarf Gestr in exchange for promising to give him his first-born son. He wins Florida, daughter of King Ptolemeus, by defeating Valbrandr, another suitor, at arms and at harp playing. Valbrandr takes revenge first by stabbing Sigrgar<'lr and then by killing the king in battle. Florida's two sons by Sigrgar<'lr are thrown into the sea, but one is rescued by a crow. King Valdimar of England frees Florida and her mother. Fifteen years later a joyful reunion takes place in England when Gestr arrives with the rescued son whom he had raised. Young Sigrgarc avenges his father's death by killing Valbrandr.

review_note: The saga relates the exploits of Sigur3r, son of King Vilhjalmr of Frakkland. Under the assumed name Asmundr, Sigurcir travels to Grikkland, where King Valdimar extends hospitality to him. When Sigurcir/ Asmundr discovers that the king keeps his daughter conceiled in a tower, he manages to reach her chambers through his skill in climbing walls and picking locks. An extended liaison ensues. For financial gains Sigurclr divulges his secrets to a wealthy man who betrays him. Sigurclr escapes seizure on three occasions through trickery. When the king discovers his true identity, however, he gladly consents to the marriage of the lovers. Sigurclr becomes king over both Frakkland and Grikkland.

review_note: Halfdan and Vilhjalmr, like Sigurclr the Silent, sons of King Lodivikus of Saxland, overcome a ferocious viking and a band of giants before Halfdan tries to win the hand of Princess Sedentiana, the maiden king of Frakkland. Halfdan and Vilhjalmr are humiliated by her. Sigurclr, who has been fostered by Count Lafranz of Lixion, kills a dragon and acquires a grateful lion. After Sigurclr and his foster-brother Randver have won many battles, they attack Sedentiana's realm. Sigurclr finally overcomes her by magic, and sleeps in three different guises with her. After rescuing other princesses from giants, Sigurclr marries Sedentiana, who in the interim has born him a son.-A chess set once owned by King Arthur is mentioned twice.

review_note:
A name given by editors to a thirteenth-century Norwegian collection of 21 short narratives with a prologue. Eighteen are translations from a group of Breton lais commonly attributed to Marie de France. The names of the tales (and their French sources) are Guiamar (Guigemar), Eskia (Fresne), Equitan (Equitan), Bisclaret (Bisclavret), Laustik (Laust1c), Desire (Desire), Tidorel (Tydorel), Chetovel (Chaitivel), Doun (Doan)'. Tveggia elskanda /Joo (Deus amanz), Gurun (source u~known), M!lun (Milun), Geitarlauf (Chievrefoi/), Strandar streng/ eikr (source unknown), Leikara lj6o (Lai du Lecheor), Janua/s lj6o (Lanval), Janet (Yonec), Naboreis (Nabaret), Ricar hinn gam/i (source unknown), Tveggia elskanda strengleikr (source unknown), Grelent ( Graelent). According to the prologue, the Strengleikar were translated at the behest of Hakon Hakonarson, King of Norway ( 12 I 7-63), from a "Book of Lais." The Strengleikar are in the oldest manuscript preserving Old Norse-Icelandic romances, the Norwegian
 Codex de la Gardie 4- 7, which also contains Elis saga and Pamphilus.

review_note:
Transmitted in three redactions, all of which derive from a lost common source. The saga is a compilation based on Dares Phrygius' De Excidio Troire, the so-called Latin Homer, Vergil's Aeneid, and Ovid's Heroides and Metamorphoses. Two conflicting theories exist regarding the origin of the saga: that it was translated into Icelandic ca. 1200; that it was translated around the middle of the thirteenth
 century at the Norwegian court of King Hakon Hakonarson (1217- 63).

review_note:
The plot devolves from the abduction by a flying dragon of Marmoria, daughter of King Fili pus of Saxland. Valdimar, her brother, sets out in search of her, assisted by a family of giants, from whom he learns that his sister has been abducted by Queen Lupa, the shape-shifting stepmother of Florida and Blabus, children of King Arkistratus. Marmoria is to be the bride of Blabus. By means of a magic harp
 Marmoria and Florida, and then Blabus, are lured to Valdimar's invisible dwelling in the woods. A massive military engagement ensues in which Lupa, in the form of a poison-spewing dragon, is finally killed. In the end feuding parties are reconciled. Valdimar marries Florida.

review_note: Together with Valvens þáttr [Percevals] saga derives from Chretien de Troyes' incomplete romance Perceval or Le conte du graal. The French romance was presumably translated into Norwegian in the thirteenth century during the reign of King Hakon Hakonarson of Norway (1217-63). The translation of vv. 1-6513 of Perceval is entitled Parcevals saga; v. 6514 to the end Valvens þáttr.

review_note: The saga relates the adventures of the foster-brothers Vik tor, son of the king of France, and Blavus, a foreign prince who possesses a flying carpet. After introductory adventures involving vikings and berserks, Viktor sets off for India to sue for the hand of Fulgida, a maiden king. After Viktor has been repeatedly humiliated, Blavus travels to India disguised as a monk, cures Fulgida of a skin disease, and exchanges shapes with her so that she can travel to France without interference from her knights. Fulgida (Blavus) agrees to marry Soldan of Serkland on the condition that R6sida, Soldan's daughter, be bridesmaid. On the wedding day Fulgida (Blavus) abducts R6sida on the flying carpet and returns to Frakkland, where the marriages of Viktor to Fulgida, and Blavus to R6sida are celebrated.

review_note: The saga is ascribed to Homer and is supposed to have been inscribed on a wall in Babylon. Vilhjalmr, son of King Rikari'lr of England, wins a magic ring and coat of mail. After overcoming a giant and a dragon, Vilhjalmr sets out to seek his missing father. He acquires a grateful lion as a companion that helps him save the life of Reginbald, son of the king of Miklagari'lr. With magical equipment provided by the beautiful Astrinomia, Vilhjalmr comes to the kingdom of Trekt in Africa, where King Katon is missing. Ermlaug, Astrinomia's fostermother, advises Vilhjalmr how to release his father from the trolls. Astrinomia and Reginbald have been seized in the meantime and must be saved. There follows a complex and repetitious tale of battles with giants and trolls conquered by the help of a certain SjMr after the lion has been killed. Vilhjalmr is finally named king of Babylon.

The able but na"ive Vilmundr, son of a man named Svicli, comes upon Gullbra while seeking a lost goat. review_note: A translation of the Anglo-Norman Boeve de Haurntone, preserved only in Icelandic manuscripts, but presumably translated into Norwegian in the thirteenth century. Bevis is the son of the earl of Hamtun whose wife caused the earl's death in order to marry the emperor of Þýzkaland. On the wedding day Bevis kills the emperor to avenge the father's death. As punishment he is sold by his mother to heathen sailors who take him to Egiptaland. The saga recounts Bevis' martial deeds, his love of the heathen J osvena, her eventual conversion to Christianity, and marriage to Bevis. The narrative is replete with imprisonments, abductions, separations, pursuits, last-minute rescues, military encounters, and mass conversions. The work ends with the natural death of Bevis and Josvena.

 AM 573, 4°. Scholars disagree whether the translation was undertaken in Iceland or in Norway.

review_note: The saga recounts Brering's efforts to avenge the death of his uncle, ruler of Ertinborg, who had been killed by one of his own knights, Heinrekr. Heinrekr proposes marriage to Brering's widowed mother, sister of the murdered ruler. Rejected, he vows to kill Ba:ringr. Mother and child flee to England, where Breringr eventually is knighted. He travels to the continent and serves under the rulers of Frakkland, Grikkland, and Romaborg, distinguishing himself in tournament and war. Several princesses fall passionately in love with him, but he rejects them. Eventually, he vanquishes Heinrekr, becomes ruler of his patrimonial as well as other lands, and marries the daughter of the king of Grikkland.

review_note:
Damusti is a pious knight at the court of King Katalaktus of Grikkland. When the king's daughter, Gratiana, marries King Jon of Smaland, Damusti kills Jon out of jealousy. Gratiana becomes fatally ill. The
 Virgin Mary appears to the repentant Damusti, tells him to arm himself and ride to the church where Gratiana lies buried. There Damusti defeats the giant Alheimr who reveals that he had induced
 Gratiana's apparent death in order to marry her himself. Alheimr gives Damusti a potion which will revive Gratiana. Katalaktus forgives Damusti and the knight marries Gratiana. When their son is old enough to rule, Damusti and Gratiana turn to the spiritual life and become hermits.

review_note:
Composed in Iceland, presumably in the fourteenth century, and extant also in two younger, abridged and altered versions. The saga recounts the various maneuvers of Dinus, the son of the king of Egypt, and Philotemia, daughter of Maximilianus of Africa, to outwit each other. They have in common the idiosyncrasy of scorning the love of all members of the opposite sex. By means of a magic apple each
 succeeds in arousing the passion of the other, however. Before the two are finally joined in marriage, they encounter spells, shape-shifting, and various degradations imposed on one another.

claim_freetext: Bossuat: Longnon suppose une rédaction primitive fin Xe, par Bertolai de Laon, un remaniement fin XIe sous l'influence de la maison de Ribemont, et le poème conservé du XII 2/2. J. Flach relève des archaïsmes juridiques incompatibles avec féodalité du XIIe. [crois me souvenir de discussion avec M. Banniard sur ce sujet. Voir sa bibliogr. Dans même volume que G. Hasenohr sur abrév., Peuples d'Europe?]. Autres indices familles de Rumigny, Florennes et Ribemont, selon F. Lot. Cf. aussi Moisan sIII. Allusion de Guilhem de Berguedan aux 4 fils de Herbert dans un sirventes de 1190 prouve que thème connu en Catalogne et que des rédactions plus anciennes existaient.
